		<item>
		<title>Fortress Power debuts high-voltage, all-in-one residential battery</title>
		<link>https://www.pv-magazine.com/2024/01/12/fortress-power-debuts-high-voltage-all-in-one-residential-battery/</link>
					<comments>https://www.pv-magazine.com/2024/01/12/fortress-power-debuts-high-voltage-all-in-one-residential-battery/#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Marija Maisch]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 12 Jan 2024 14:15:56 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Distributed Storage]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Energy Storage]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[A-ES Series hybrid inverter]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[all in one residential battery]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Battery storage]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Electric Vehicles]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Fortress Power]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[high voltage battery]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Renewables]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[residential battery]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[solar energy]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.pv-magazine.com/?p=241333</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Fortress Power's Avalon High Voltage Energy Storage System combines a hybrid inverter, high-voltage battery, and a smart energy panel in an all-in-one, whole-home backup system.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Fortress Power's Avalon High Voltage Energy Storage System combines a hybrid inverter, high-voltage battery, and a smart energy panel in an all-in-one, whole-home backup system.</span></p><p>US-based Fortress Power has announced its entry into the high-voltage energy storage residential market. It marked this milestone with the installation of its first residential Avalon System in late December.</p>
<p>The Avalon HV ESS system features a smart energy panel, customizable battery stack, and inverter. The system works inside and outside and is scalable up from 14.4 kWh to 176 kWh. It can be DC- or AC-coupled, with 200 A pass-through.</p>
<p>Operating at 200 V to 300 V at the DC terminal, the Avalon System closely matches PV array voltage, reducing the need for DC to DC conversion which, according to the manufacturer, enhances overall operational efficiency by approximately from 6 to 8%.<span data-ccp-props="{&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559685&quot;:720,&quot;335559739&quot;:160,&quot;335559740&quot;:259}"> </span></p>
<p>The system includes a 7.6 kW or 11.4 kW inverter. It has four MPPTs with a voltage range of 80 V to 520 V and maximum input current per string of 16 A.</p>
<p>The Avalon Smart Energy Panel manages large loads in the house to stop the inverter from tripping. It can intelligently manage up to twelve different 120 V circuits, six 240 V circuits, or any combination, providing flexible whole home backup without a dedicated emergency power panel.<span data-ccp-props="{&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559685&quot;:720,&quot;335559739&quot;:160,&quot;335559740&quot;:259}"> </span></p>
<p>With the integrated smart load panel, pre-installed AC coupling circuit, 200 A pass-through and straightforward EV charger installation, the Avalon System reduces the need for extra components, such as back up panel, AC combiner, separate smart load panel, bypass, and other, the manufacturer says.</p>
<p>Avalon boast a cycle life of more than 8,000 cycles and comes with a 10-year warranty. The system is based on tier 1 automotive grade lithium iron phosphate (LFP) battery cells.</p>
<p>Furthermore, for homeowners, Avalon could be turned into a source of revenue through the company's EnergyBroker program by selling energy into wholesale markets or to extra energy.</p>
<p>&#8220;This helps achieve a shorter payback period while contributing to a more resilient and efficient power grid,&#8221; Fortress Power says.</p>]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://www.pv-magazine.com/2024/01/12/fortress-power-debuts-high-voltage-all-in-one-residential-battery/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">241333</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Dark December for northern Europe, sunny in the South</title>
		<link>https://www.pv-magazine.com/2024/01/12/dark-december-for-northern-europe-sunny-in-the-south/</link>
					<comments>https://www.pv-magazine.com/2024/01/12/dark-december-for-northern-europe-sunny-in-the-south/#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[pv magazine]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 12 Jan 2024 14:01:38 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Commercial & Industrial PV]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Markets]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Opinion & Analysis]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Residential PV]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Utility Scale PV]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[photovoltaic]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[photovoltaics]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PV]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PV modules]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PV plant]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[renewable energies]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Renewables]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[residential PV]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Rooftop PV]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[rooftop solar]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Solar]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[solar energy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[solar modules]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[solar panels]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Solar Power]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Solar PV]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.pv-magazine.com/?p=241453</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[In a new weekly update for <b>pv magazine</b>, Solcast, a DNV company, reports that increased cloud led to solar assets in Northern Germany and the Netherlands receiving only 70% of normal irradiance in December. This cloud activity, however, did not make it below the Alps, and Southern Europe saw reduced rain and significantly less cloud than normal, with some regions experiencing 130% of the normal December irradiance.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="p1"><span class="s1">In a new weekly update for <b>pv magazine</b>, Solcast, a DNV company, reports that increased cloud led to solar assets in Northern Germany and the Netherlands receiving only 70% of normal irradiance in December. This cloud activity, however, did not make it below the Alps, and Southern Europe saw reduced rain and significantly less cloud than normal, with some regions experiencing 130% of the normal December irradiance.</span></p><p>A series of intense low pressure systems extending from the Baltics to the UK pulled moisture off of the Atlantic, bringing cloud and resulting in lower irradiance over Northern, Central and Western Europe this December. This increased cloud led to solar assets in Northern Germany and the Netherlands receiving only 70% of normal irradiance, according to data collected by Solcast, a DNV company, via the <a href="https://solcast.com//?utm_source=pvmag&utm_medium=Content&utm_campaign=ghimap" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Solcast API</a>. Due to short winter days, this is off of an extremely low base average.</p>
<p>This cloud activity did not make it below the Alps, and Southern Europe saw reduced rain and significantly less cloud than normal, with some regions experiencing 130% of the normal December irradiance.</p>
<p><img data-attachment-id="241456" data-permalink="https://www.pv-magazine.com/2024/01/12/dark-december-for-northern-europe-sunny-in-the-south/deviation_europe_december23/" data-orig-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23.png" data-orig-size="4096,2670" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Deviation_Europe_December23" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Solcast Analysis 2023&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23-600x391.png" data-large-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23-1200x782.png" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" class="size-medium wp-image-241456 aligncenter" src="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23-600x391.png" alt="" width="600" height="391" srcset="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23-600x391.png 600w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23-1200x782.png 1200w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23-768x501.png 768w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23-1536x1001.png 1536w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Deviation_Europe_December23-2048x1335.png 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></p>
<p>Despite the cold and snowy start to the month, with heavy snowfall bringing both reduced irradiance and snow soiling for solar assets, most of the continent saw a relatively mild month. This pattern is in line with a normal El Nino year, typically seeing milder and wetter weather to the start of winter in Northern Europe, becoming colder and drier as the months continue. Southern Europe also saw warmer than normal temperatures, following the trend of 2023 as the hottest year on record and approaching a 1.5-degree increase from climatological averages.</p>
<p><img data-attachment-id="241457" data-permalink="https://www.pv-magazine.com/2024/01/12/dark-december-for-northern-europe-sunny-in-the-south/averagedaily_europe_december23/" data-orig-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23.png" data-orig-size="4096,2647" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="AverageDaily_Europe_December23" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Solcast Analysis 2023&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23-600x388.png" data-large-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23-1200x775.png" decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-241457 aligncenter" src="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23-600x388.png" alt="" width="600" height="388" srcset="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23-600x388.png 600w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23-1200x775.png 1200w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23-768x496.png 768w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23-1536x993.png 1536w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/AverageDaily_Europe_December23-2048x1324.png 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></p>
<p>While solar production in Northern Europe was suppressed, December saw records for wind power fall due to the strong winds driven by several significant storms. Late in the month Storms Pia and Gerrit disrupted holiday travel plans but also helped both the UK and Germany reach new records for wind generation. This helped Germany keep on track to exceed 50% of power from renewable sources across 2023, despite the reduced contribution from Solar generation in winter.</p>
<p>The effects of these storms were significant, as you can see from the below daily GHI image from December 21st, cloud associated with Storm Pia blocked irradiance from Scotland to the Pyrenees.</p>
<figure id="attachment_241458" style="width: 600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="241458" data-permalink="https://www.pv-magazine.com/2024/01/12/dark-december-for-northern-europe-sunny-in-the-south/dailyghi_20231221/" data-orig-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221.png" data-orig-size="4096,2651" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="DailyGHI_20231221" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Solcast Analysis 2023&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221-600x388.png" data-large-file="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221-1200x777.png" decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-241458" src="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221-600x388.png" alt="" width="600" height="388" srcset="https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221-600x388.png 600w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221-1200x777.png 1200w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221-768x497.png 768w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221-1536x994.png 1536w, https://www.pv-magazine.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/DailyGHI_20231221-2048x1326.png 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Solcast Analysis 2023 <p><i>Image: Solcast</i></p>
</figcaption></figure>
<p><em><a href="https://solcast.com/?utm_source=pvmag&utm_medium=Content&utm_campaign=ghimap">Solcast</a> produces these figures by tracking clouds and aerosols at 1-2km resolution globally, using satellite data and proprietary <a href="https://solcast.com/irradiance-data-methodology/?utm_source=pvmag&utm_medium=Content&utm_campaign=ghimap">AI/ML algorithms</a>. This data is used to drive irradiance models, enabling Solcast to calculate irradiance at high resolution, with typical bias of less than 2%, and also cloud-tracking forecasts. This information is used by more than 300 companies managing over 150 GW of solar assets throughout the world.</em></p>]]></content:encoded>
					
